      "title": "See also"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Broadcasting rules apply, see the "
            },
            {
              "external_url": "https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.linalg.html",
              "href": "",
              "kind": "link",
              "target": "linalg",
              "text": "we.linalg"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " documentation for\ndetails."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "This is implemented using the "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "_geev"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " LAPACK routines which compute\nthe eigenvalues and eigenvectors of general square arrays."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "The number "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "w"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " is an eigenvalue of "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "a"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " if there exists a vector "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "v"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " such\nthat "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "a @ v = w * v"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ". Thus, the arrays "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "a"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "eigenvalues"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ", and\n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "eigenvectors"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " satisfy the equations "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "a @ eigenvectors[:,i] =\neigenvalues[i] * eigenvectors[:,i]"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " for "
            },
            {
              "kind": "math",
              "latex": "i \\in \\{0,...,M-1\\}"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "The array "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "eigenvectors"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " may not be of maximum rank, that is, some of the\ncolumns may be linearly dependent, although round-off error may obscure\nthat fact. If the eigenvalues are all different, then theoretically the\neigenvectors are linearly independent and "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "a"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " can be diagonalized by a\nsimilarity transformation using "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "eigenvectors"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ", i.e, "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "inv(eigenvectors) @\na @ eigenvectors"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " is diagonal."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "For non-Hermitian normal matrices the SciPy function "
            },
            {
              "external_url": "https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/generated/scipy.linalg.schur.html",
              "href": "",
              "kind": "link",
              "target": "scipy.linalg.schur",
              "text": "scipy.linalg.schur"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "\nis preferred because the matrix "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "eigenvectors"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " is guaranteed to be\nunitary, which is not the case when using "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "eig"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ". The Schur factorization\nproduces an upper triangular matrix rather than a diagonal matrix, but for\nnormal matrices only the diagonal of the upper triangular matrix is\nneeded, the rest is roundoff error."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Finally, it is emphasized that "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "eigenvectors"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " consists of the "
            },
            {
              "kind": "emphasis",
              "text": "right"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " (as\nin right-hand side) eigenvectors of "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "a"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ". A vector "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "y"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " satisfying "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "y.T @ a\n= z * y.T"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " for some number "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "z"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " is called a "
            },
            {
              "kind": "emphasis",
              "text": "left"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " eigenvector of "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "a"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ",\nand, in general, the left and right eigenvectors of a matrix are not\nnecessarily the (perhaps conjugate) transposes of each other."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Notes"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "G. Strang, "
            },
            {
              "kind": "emphasis",
              "text": "Linear Algebra and Its Applications"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ", 2nd Ed., Orlando, FL,\nAcademic Press, Inc., 1980, Various pp."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "title": "References"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "lines": [
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "import whest as we"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "from numpy import linalg as LA"
            }
          ],
          "type": "doctest_block"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "(Almost) trivial example with real eigenvalues and eigenvectors."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "lines": [
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "eigenvalues, eigenvectors = LA.eig(we.diag((1, 2, 3)))"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "eigenvalues"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "array([1., 2., 3.])"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "eigenvectors"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "array([[1., 0., 0.],"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "       [0., 1., 0.],"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "       [0., 0., 1.]])"
            }
          ],
          "type": "doctest_block"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Real matrix possessing complex eigenvalues and eigenvectors;\nnote that the eigenvalues are complex conjugates of each other."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "lines": [
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "eigenvalues, eigenvectors = LA.eig(we.array([[1, -1], [1, 1]]))"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "eigenvalues"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "array([1.+1.j, 1.-1.j])"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "eigenvectors"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "array([[0.70710678+0.j        , 0.70710678-0.j        ],"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "       [0.        -0.70710678j, 0.        +0.70710678j]])"
            }
          ],
          "type": "doctest_block"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Complex-valued matrix with real eigenvalues (but complex-valued\neigenvectors); note that "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "a.conj().T == a"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ", i.e., "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "a"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " is Hermitian."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "lines": [
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "a = we.array([[1, 1j], [-1j, 1]])"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "eigenvalues, eigenvectors = LA.eig(a)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "eigenvalues"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "array([2.+0.j, 0.+0.j])"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "eigenvectors"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "array([[ 0.        +0.70710678j,  0.70710678+0.j        ], # may vary"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "       [ 0.70710678+0.j        , -0.        +0.70710678j]])"
            }
          ],
          "type": "doctest_block"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Be careful about round-off error!"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "lines": [
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "a = we.array([[1 + 1e-9, 0], [0, 1 - 1e-9]])"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "# Theor. eigenvalues are 1 +/- 1e-9"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "eigenvalues, eigenvectors = LA.eig(a)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "eigenvalues"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "array([1., 1.])"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "eigenvectors"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "array([[1., 0.],"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "       [0., 1.]])"
            }
          ],
          "type": "doctest_block"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Examples"
    }
